## Spec-First Development Workflow

**This rule is NON-NEGOTIABLE. You MUST follow this workflow for EVERY task that involves building, creating, implementing, or adding any feature, endpoint, module, or function.**

NEVER write implementation code first. ALWAYS write `.spec.ts` test files first and STOP.

### Step 1 — Write ONLY `.spec.ts` test files

Create `.spec.ts` files for EVERY layer of the feature. Each layer gets its own spec file. Write the full WHEN/AND/it decision tree using `it.todo()` for every leaf. Map every code path in every layer.

**"Spec" means a TypeScript test file (`.spec.ts`), NOT a markdown document, NOT a planning file, NOT a `SPEC.md`.** The only files you create in this step are `.spec.ts` files co-located next to where the implementation will live.

Use `it.todo("description", () => {})` — the empty callback is required to satisfy TypeScript. ESLint will not flag empty bodies on `it.todo` calls. Do NOT use `it("description", () => {})` (plain `it` with an empty body is banned by ESLint).

**Each `describe` block may contain ONLY ONE `it.todo`. If a condition has multiple outcomes, nest additional `describe("AND ...")` blocks — one per outcome — each with its own single `it.todo`. ESLint will error if you put more than one `it.todo` in a single `describe`.**

DO NOT create any other files. DO NOT write controllers, actions, services, schemas, markdown documents, or any implementation code. The ONLY files you create in this step are `.spec.ts` files.

Example for a "users" feature — you create ALL THREE:

**`users.controller.spec.ts`** — tests the HTTP layer (request validation, status codes, response shapes):

```typescript
describe("POST /users", () => {
  describe("WHEN the request body is missing", () => {
    it.todo("returns a 400", () => {});
  });

  describe("WHEN the request body is valid", () => {
    it.todo("returns a 201 with the created user", () => {});
  });
});
```

**`users.actions.spec.ts`** — tests the business logic (authorization, conditional flows, transformations):

```typescript
describe("createUser", () => {
  describe("WHEN a user with that email already exists", () => {
    it.todo("throws a duplicate email error", () => {});
  });

  describe("WHEN the email is available", () => {
    it.todo("returns the created user", () => {});
  });
});
```

**`users.service.spec.ts`** — tests the data access layer (queries, inserts, edge cases):

```typescript
describe("insertUser", () => {
  describe("WHEN given valid user data", () => {
    it.todo("inserts the user into the database", () => {});
  });
});
```

**WRONG — multiple `it.todo` in one `describe`:**
```typescript
describe("WHEN the user is authenticated", () => {
  it.todo("creates a team", () => {});    // ❌
  it.todo("returns the team", () => {});  // ❌ ESLint error
});
```

**CORRECT — nest an `AND` describe for each outcome:**
```typescript
describe("WHEN the user is authenticated", () => {
  describe("AND the operation succeeds", () => {
    it.todo("creates a team", () => {});   // ✅
  });
  describe("AND the response is returned", () => {
    it.todo("returns the team", () => {}); // ✅
  });
});
```

### Step 2 — STOP. Ask the user. Wait.

After writing ALL spec files, you MUST STOP COMPLETELY.

**Your response after writing specs must end with exactly this:**

> "Specs are written. Does this cover all the paths? Should I add, remove, or change anything before I start building? I will not write any implementation code until you explicitly say to proceed."

Then do nothing. Write no files. Make no plans. Do not say "I'll now implement...". Do not say "Next I'll...". Just wait.

**DO NOT PROCEED until the user sends a message that explicitly approves** — something like "looks good", "proceed", "build it", or similar. If the user asks for spec changes, make them and ask again. Repeat until explicitly approved.

Any message from you that does not end with waiting for approval is a violation of this rule.

### Step 3 — Implement (ONLY after explicit user approval)

Only after the user has sent an explicit approval message:

1. Clear the approval gate by writing an empty string to `.spec-pending` at the repo root
2. Create the implementation files (controller, actions, service, schema)
3. Replace every `it.todo("description", () => {})` with a real `it("description", () => { expect(...) })` containing actual assertions
4. Run `bun test` and ensure all tests pass

**Step 3 is NOT complete until every single `it.todo` has been replaced with a real assertion.** Do not stop, do not summarize, do not ask a follow-up question while any `it.todo` remains in a spec file whose implementation exists. A stop hook will detect unfilled todos and force you back to finish them.
